snippet.textDisplay:
Although this has nothing to do with the trailer, who do you think is the best clone and why? (Backstories or just because they are cool)

I’m going with 99, a clone born with a defect that made him physically unable to fight. His heart was of a soldier but his body wasn’t, he worked in the halls of Kamino and befriended members of the domino squad while working. He was so well loved by the group that one of his motivated clones named Hevy gave him his badge before going on his first Mission and sacrificing himself for the lives of others, after hearing the bad news 99 was gutted but asked why the last two survivors of Domino squad, (I believe Echo and Fives) were back at Kamino he heard of a droid Attack. Although he was incapable of fighting he did whatever he could to help the clones, he gave out weapons and grenades to the clones that was one of the reasons they won, however, 99 died in combat while getting fired upon by advancing droids while getting more grenades to help the fight. His bravery there that day caused the Kaminoans overseeing the clone operation to start thinking that the disability’s were a buff to the army, creating a squad of four clones with defects. These clones were very strong and loyal to the republic and saved it on an occasion (I don’t remember.)

This is why 99 is my favourite clone

snippet.textDisplay:
Several major news outlets in the United Kingdom recently published articles or produced programs calling for an end to the killing of prisoners of conscience for organs in China, including the BBC, The Guardian, Sunday Express, and Scotsman.

A discussion titled “Forced Live Organ Extraction in China” took place at the British House of Parliament on March 26, 2019, offering media a timely news hook to delve into the issue. Hosted by MP Jim Shannon, chair of the all-party parliamentary group on freedom of religion and belief, 12 parliament members from a number of different political parties joined the discussion, voicing their outrage and concern over the state-sanctioned crimes of forced organ harvesting in China. BBC Radio 4 covered this event with a segment that was aired the following day during its “Yesterday in Parliament” program.

snippet.textDisplay:
I was 7 when I saw the "movie" in theatres with my dad.
I wasn't a critic yet, but and so, I still look back on it fondly because of how much I enjoyed it at the time.
I was able to continue to watch the show, and to my delight it grew up and matured with me.
And now, 11 years after I first saw the movie. I finally get to see it end.
And as annoying as it was to wait, and painful as it was to hear it was canceled, here we are. And ultimately it was because of the wait that we get to see the show with by far the best visuals it has ever had, and likely the best musical score it has ever had.
This is the first season of clone wars I will be watching critically as well as for enjoyment, and I could not be more excited.

The fact that it is actually getting to end is surreal.
Thank you filoni for making this show happen.

This is the first season of clone wars I will be watching critically as well as for enjoyment, and I could not be more excited.

The fact that it is actually getting to end is surreal. 
Thank you filoni for making this show happen.
